## 2026-07-04 — Add Connections entity (external-source OAuth: MyAnimeList)
- What:
  - New `connection` domain/entity storing OAuth creds+tokens per external
    provider (MyAnimeList now; IMDB is a one-line registry addition). Full CRUD
    plus PKCE authorize → callback → refresh flow under `/v1/connections` (write-
    gated). Secrets/tokens are AES-256-GCM encrypted at rest and redacted from
    every response via `json:"-"`.
  - Provider endpoint registry lives in `domain` (single source of truth shared
    by the service's authorize-URL builder and the outbound OAuth client) so the
    repository layer does not import service (keeps strict downward layering).
  - KV-backed single-use StateStore for PKCE state; migration 0005; new secret
    `CONNECTIONS_ENC_KEY` (32-byte, validated) wired through config/worker/env.
- Why: Frontend needs a managed store of external-source OAuth connections.
- Files: internal/domain/connection.go; migrations/0005_connections.sql;
  internal/repository/d1/connection_repo.go; internal/repository/oauth/client.go;
  internal/repository/kv/state_store.go; internal/service/{crypto,oauth_providers,
  connection_service,ports}.go; internal/handler/{connection_handler,ports}.go;
  internal/server/router.go; internal/app/module.go; internal/config/config.go;
  worker/index.ts; wrangler.jsonc; .env.example; .mockery.yaml + regenerated
  mocks + swagger.
- Tests: added domain (Valid/consts/endpoints/JSON-redaction), d1 repo (CRUD +
  SaveTokens SQL/params), service (crypto round-trip + Create/Update/Authorize/
  Callback/Refresh incl. encryption + error paths), handler (status codes, bind
  errors, writeError mapping, response redaction). `go build/vet` clean;
  `go test ./...` → 205 pass; gated pkg coverage: domain 100%, service 88.7%,
  handler 87.9%, d1 82.7% (all ≥80%).
- Notes: FOLLOW-UPS for the user (not done here) — apply migration
  `wrangler d1 execute manga --file=migrations/0005_connections.sql`,
  `wrangler secret put CONNECTIONS_ENC_KEY` (32 bytes), then deploy.
  `make cover` errors in this env with `go: no such tool "covdata"` (pre-existing
  toolchain issue in the merge step, unrelated to this change); per-package
  `go test -cover` numbers above are authoritative. Deviations: (1) provider
  endpoint registry placed in `domain` rather than `internal/service/
  oauth_providers.go` to avoid the repository→service upward import the strict
  layering rule forbids (service still owns authorize-URL construction in
  oauth_providers.go); (2) client_id is stored/served in plaintext (not a secret,
  present in the JSON contract), so only client_secret/tokens are encrypted.

## 2026-07-04 — CORS for the admin panel (Hertz middleware)
- What: added hertz-contrib/cors global middleware in internal/server/router.go
  (echoes allowed Origin, handles the OPTIONS preflight → 204). Allowlist comes
  from HTTP.CORSAllowOrigins (new), read from CORS_ALLOW_ORIGINS env, default
  "https://griyamedia.brata.cloud,http://localhost:3000". The env is declared in
  wrangler.jsonc and passed through to the container in worker/index.ts.
- Why: the admin panel is a different origin than the API and reaches it via the
  cloudflared tunnel (griyamedia-tunnel.brata.cloud) straight to Hertz — bypassing
  the fronting Worker — so authenticated fetches were preflighted and 404'd (no
  OPTIONS route, no CORS). Fixing it in Hertz covers both the tunnel and Worker
  paths; an earlier Worker-only attempt didn't, since the tunnel skips the Worker.
- Files: internal/server/router.go, internal/config/config.go, worker/index.ts,
  wrangler.jsonc, go.mod, go.sum
- Tests: `go build ./...` + `go vet ./internal/...` pass; gofmt clean. internal/
  server & internal/config are infra (exempt from the 80% bar). Redeploy required;
  for local/tunnel dev the Go server picks up the default allowlist.

## 2026-07-04 — Fix duplicate CORS header on OIDC discovery endpoint
- What: disabled the zitadel OP's built-in CORS layer via `op.WithCORSOptions(nil)`
  in internal/oidc/provider.go, so CORS is owned solely by the Hertz global
  middleware (router.go).
- Why: zitadel's default CORS echoes any request Origin into
  Access-Control-Allow-Origin, duplicating the header the Hertz cors middleware
  already sets on OP-served routes (e.g. /.well-known/openid-configuration).
  Browsers reject responses carrying two Access-Control-Allow-Origin values
  ("contains multiple values 'http://localhost:3000, http://localhost:3000'"),
  breaking the admin panel's OIDC discovery / signin.
- Files: internal/oidc/provider.go
- Tests: go build ./... + go vet ./internal/oidc/... clean; go test ./... → 205 pass.

## 2026-07-04 — Fix: JWT access tokens carried no `scope` claim (all gated routes 403)
- What: implemented `GetPrivateClaimsFromScopes` in internal/oidc/storage.go to
  emit the granted scopes as a `scope` private claim (was `return nil, nil`).
- Why: zitadel's JWT builder (op.CreateJWT) never sets the standard `scope` claim
  itself — it only merges private claims from this method. With it empty, every
  JWT shipped without `scope`, so the Bearer middleware's scope gate saw an empty
  claims.Scopes and rejected every valid token on manga.read/manga.write routes
  (e.g. admin panel's GET/POST /v1/connections, media/chapter/taxonomy CRUD).
  Latent since the gate was added; surfaced now that the admin panel exercises
  gated routes in a real browser.
- Files: internal/oidc/storage.go
- Tests: go build ./... + go vet ./internal/oidc/... clean; go test ./... → 205
  pass. Verified end-to-end with a throwaway round-trip test (removed): the minted
  token JSON now contains `"scope":"openid offline_access manga.write manga.read"`
  and unmarshals back into claims.Scopes so hasScope() matches. internal/oidc is
  coverage-exempt infra.

## 2026-07-04 — Gate /v1/connections behind a dedicated connections.write scope
- What:
  - New scope const ScopeConnectionsWrite="connections.write" (internal/oidc/util.go),
    added to the OP's SupportedScopes (provider.go) and the admin-web seed (seed.go).
  - Fixed Client.IsScopeAllowed (client.go): was `return scope == ScopeMangaWrite`,
    which silently dropped manga.read and would drop connections.write in the
    auth-code flow (zitadel ValidateAuthReqScopes deletes any non-standard scope
    IsScopeAllowed rejects). Now allows manga.read/manga.write/connections.write.
  - Moved the 8 /v1/connections routes out of the manga.write `manage` group into
    their own group gated by MiddlewareScope(connections.write) (router.go).
- Why: managing upstream OAuth credentials (MyAnimeList etc.) should be authorized
  separately from catalog writes.
- Files: internal/oidc/util.go, internal/oidc/provider.go, internal/oidc/client.go,
  internal/oidc/seed.go, internal/server/router.go
- Tests: go build ./... + go vet ./internal/... clean; go test ./... → 205 pass.
  internal/oidc + internal/server are coverage-exempt infra.
- Ops: existing admin-web client row already in D1 won't be re-seeded — add the
  scope manually (SQL below) and re-login to mint a token carrying it.

## 2026-07-04 — Per-kind taxonomy write scopes (taksonomi.<kind>.write); reads use manga.read
- What:
  - Added per-kind taxonomy write scopes taksonomi.<kind>.write (kind ∈ genres |
    categories | authors | artists): helper ScopeTaxonomyWrite + TaxonomyWriteKinds
    (util.go), advertised in SupportedScopes (provider.go), allowed in
    Client.IsScopeAllowed (client.go), seeded on admin-web (seed.go).
  - New Provider.MiddlewareTaxonomyWrite() resolves the required scope from the
    :kind path param at request time (refactored the internal middleware to take a
    per-request scope resolver instead of a fixed string). Unknown kinds resolve to
    no scope and fall through to the handler's 404.
  - router.go: GET /v1/taxonomies/:kind moved to the manga.read group; POST/PUT/
    DELETE moved to a new group gated by MiddlewareTaxonomyWrite(). Same set of
    (method, path) pairs as before, only the middleware chain changed.
- Why: let each taxonomy kind's write access be delegated independently, while
  taxonomy reads only need the existing reader scope.
- Files: internal/oidc/util.go, provider.go, client.go, seed.go, middleware.go,
  internal/server/router.go
- Tests: go build ./... + go vet ./internal/... clean; gofmt clean; go test ./... →
  205 pass. internal/oidc + internal/server are coverage-exempt infra.
- Ops: existing admin-web D1 row won't be re-seeded — add the 4 new scopes and
  re-login (see message for SQL). Admin panel must request taksonomi.<kind>.write.

## 2026-07-04 — Unified response envelope for all REST responses
- What: every internal/handler response and the OIDC resource-server auth errors
  now share one shape — success {"success":true,"data":<typed>}, error
  {"success":false,"message":<msg>,"error_code":<code>}. Envelope is the generic
  domain.APIResponse[T] with a flat message/error_code (no nested error object)
  (internal/domain/response.go); generic handler helper writeOK[T] + writeErr +
  refactored writeError (response.go); all handler c.JSON sites converted; oidc
  middleware unauthorized/forbidden emit domain.APIResponse[any] (middleware.go).
  handler.ErrorResponse is a flat doc struct for the swagger @Failure annotations.
- Why: give clients (admin panel / iOS) a single, predictable response structure.
- Scope note: the OAuth/OIDC protocol endpoints (/oauth/token, discovery, JWKS,
  DCR) are intentionally NOT wrapped — they must keep their RFC-defined bodies.
  204 No Content deletes keep an empty body (nothing to wrap).
- Files: internal/domain/response.go, internal/handler/{response,connection,
  convert,media,taxonomy,video,novel,health}_handler.go, internal/handler/
  helpers_test.go + media_handler_test.go, internal/oidc/middleware.go
- Tests: go build ./... + go vet ./internal/... clean; gofmt clean; go test ./...
  → 205 pass. Verified wire shape: success {"success":true,"data":{...}},
  error {"success":false,"error":{"code":...,"message":...}}.
- Follow-up (not done): swagger @Success/@Failure annotations still describe the
  inner types, not the envelope — regenerate/rewrite in a later pass.

## 2026-07-05 — Pagination metadata in response headers (offset + cursor)
- What: pagination data now rides in response headers instead of only the body.
  New domain.Pagination (offset|cursor) with OffsetPagination/CursorPagination
  constructors + domain.CatalogPageSize (internal/domain/pagination.go). New
  handler.writePagination emits X-Pagination-Kind / -Has-Next / -Per-Page /
  -Page / -Total / -Next-Cursor / -Prev-Cursor, and queryCursor parses the
  cursor param (internal/handler/pagination.go). Wired into the offset-paginated
  catalog list endpoints (popular/latest/search). Cursor strategy is fully
  supported by the helper (constructor + header branch + query parser), ready to
  wire when a cursor endpoint lands.
- Why: requested — pagination should be readable from headers and support either
  skip/offset or cursor pagination via one helper.
- CORS: handler.PaginationHeaders added to the cors ExposeHeaders (router.go) so
  the cross-origin admin panel can read the headers.
- Files: internal/domain/pagination.go (new), internal/handler/pagination.go
  (new), internal/handler/media_handler.go, internal/service/media_service.go
  (30 -> domain.CatalogPageSize), internal/server/router.go,
  internal/handler/internal_test.go (writePagination + queryCursor tests).
- Tests: go build ./... + go vet ./internal/... clean; gofmt clean; go test ./...
  → 210 pass; internal/handler coverage 88.2% (>80% gate). Verified live: a
  Popular response carries X-Pagination-Kind:offset, -Page:2, -Per-Page:30,
  -Has-Next:true, and omits -Total when unknown.

## 2026-07-05 — Admin user management API + users.read/users.write scopes
- What:
  - Two new scopes ScopeUsersRead="users.read" / ScopeUsersWrite="users.write"
    (util.go), advertised in SupportedScopes (provider.go), allowed in
    Client.IsScopeAllowed (client.go), seeded on admin-web (seed.go).
  - New internal/oidc/user_admin.go: UserAdminHandler with List/Get/Create/Update/
    Delete over the admin_user table (mirrors the DCRHandler precedent — shares the
    argon2id hashing + user table). Create/Update validate email + 8-char password;
    Update leaves the password unchanged when blank; Delete refuses the last user.
    Wired via oidc.NewUserAdminHandler (module.go).
  - router.go: GET /v1/users[/:id] gated by users.read; POST/PUT/DELETE by users.write.
- Why: let the admin panel manage the accounts that can sign into the embedded OP.
- Files: internal/oidc/{util,provider,client,seed,user_admin}.go,
  internal/app/module.go, internal/server/router.go
- Tests: go build ./... + go vet clean; gofmt clean; go test ./... → 205 pass.
  internal/oidc is coverage-exempt infra. Responses are bare (record/array;
  {error,message} on error) to match the admin client; swagger regen (make docs) is
  a pending follow-up (annotations reference oidc.userRecord/userErrorBody).
- Ops: existing admin-web D1 row won't be re-seeded — add "users.read","users.write"
